[5]
Date: Wed 12 Sep 2007
Source: The Telegraph [edited]
<http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/main.jhtml?xml=/news/2007/09/12/nfoot612.xml>

Pirbright back in spotlight over foot and mouth
-----------------------------------------------------
Analysis
Only last week [3-7 Sep 2007] the chief
veterinary officer Debby Reynolds confidently
announced that FMD had been eradicated following
the disastrous outbreak linked to a
Government-run laboratory in Pirbright, Surrey.
The Department for the Environment, Food and
Rural Affairs assured farmers that its response
to last month's [August 2007] outbreak had been
so thorough that there was no danger of further infection.
However, those pronouncements have come back to
haunt Environment Secretary Hilary Benn as FMD
was discovered on a farm just 10 miles [16 km]
from Pirbright -- news met with anger and
disbelief in equal measure in the farming community.
So just how could FMD have returned to the UK?
Tony Wilsmore, a veterinary epidemiologist from
the University of Reading, said it was "highly
unlikely" that yesterday's outbreak in Egham
could have come from anywhere other than
Pirbright or the 2 farms near the laboratory
which had been infected. "The big question now is
how it could have been transferred despite all
the precautions that were taken."
Graham Brooks, president of the British Cattle
Veterinary Association, said it was possible
there had been a biosecurity breach either from
the Pirbright site -- where FMD vaccine is
handled -- or the 2 neighbouring farms after FMD
was identified last month [August 2007].
"If it turns out [to] be the same strain of the
virus as Pirbright, then it can only have been
transferred by the movement of people or vehicles
from the Pirbright site or the 2 farms nearby,"
he said. "It is unlikely to have been passed
directly from livestock to livestock because of
the distances involved. "If it subsequently
emerges that such a transfer happened after the
Pirbright infection, then the precautions which were taken have failed."
Mr. Wilsmore said a more likely scenario was that
the FMD virus had been transferred to the fields
in Egham before the Pirbright outbreak was
discovered. "Studies have shown that the FMD
virus can survive for up to 20 weeks given the
right conditions, particularly in cool, damp,
dark places such as hay bales. It can also
survive in water for around 50 days, so we are
within those parameters. "My guess is that the
virus may have been transferred from the
Pirbright area to Egham before the Pirbright
alert, and that the virus has survived in Egham
until, perhaps, the farmer put his cattle in an
infected field where they contracted it in the last 3 to 7 days."
Intriguingly, the last restrictions on livestock
movement were lifted on Saturday [8 Sep 2007] --
meaning the farmer whose cattle have been culled
may have moved them to the infected field over
the weekend, thinking they would be safe.
Such a scenario would suggest the Government had
lifted the ban on livestock movements too soon.
It would also mean there is a danger that the
virus is lying undiscovered on other farms,
almost anywhere in the country, where it could yet infect more livestock.
Microbiologist Professor Hugh Pennington, of
Aberdeen University, suggested the virus could
have spread from Pirbright through streams. "We
suspect last month's outbreak came from a waste
pipe in the Pirbright laboratories which was
swamped by flood water that was then picked up on
the wheels of lorries," he said. "I don't know
the geography of Surrey, but investigators will
look at whether the infected water could have
found its way to Egham, where it has contaminated
material that the animals there have come into contact with."
There is likely to be fierce debate over the
Government's decision not to vaccinate or cull
animals on farms near the last outbreak, said Mr. Wilsmore.
"The Government's view was that a contiguous cull
was not necessary, and that vaccination would be
the wrong thing to do because vaccinated animals
can still catch FMD but not display the symptoms
for a considerable time. The feeling was that it
was better not to vaccinate, so that any outbreak would be identified quickly.
"Obviously the Government will now face serious
questions over whether that was the right
decision." Mr Brooks said the investigation into
the cause of the latest outbreak would centre on
vehicle and livestock movements to and from the
Pirbright area. "The Health and Safety
Executive's report into the August outbreak
concluded that FMD was transferred from the
Pirbright laboratories to neighbouring farms via
soil on lorries which went in and out of the site.
"The investigation into today's events will focus
on whether any vehicles could have picked up
infected material in the Pirbright area and
transferred it to Egham. It will also try to
discover whether the farmer in Egham bought
animals from the Pirbright area before that
outbreak was discovered, and of course the
movement of vehicles in and out of his fields and
farm will be tracked to see if the virus has spread elsewhere."
[Byline: Gordon Rayner]
--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[On top of the stamping out and other containment
activities on the affected holding(s), another
crucial task on the hands of the UK Veterinary
Services is the rapid investigations of any
movements of animals, fomites, humans or vehicles
from the affected site to other locations during
the recent period. It is not clear if the
"Temporary Control Zone," reportedly placed
around a premises in Dereham, Norfolk, as "a
precautionary measure." has been applied due to
such contact or suspicion thereof.
The analysis in item [5] includes several
speculations on the time, source and route of the
FMD virus introduction into the Egham farm. The
list of speculative scenarios can be even more
exhaustive but it seems preferable to await the
results of the epidemiological investigation
which is certainly being carried out.
Subscribers may consider viewing the map which
shows the boundaries of the protection and surveillance zones, available at
<http://www.defra.gov.uk/footandmouth/pdf/declaration-pzsz120907.pdf>.
According to DEFRA's update, the affected farm in
Egham "comprises a number of separate parcels of
land." As it appears on the map, there are about
10 amalgamated protection zones, each with a
radius of 3 km around a parcel or holding. - Mod.AS]
